## 9. Earth Engine Apps

### Publicar App desde Code Editor:
```javascript
// Crear UI
var panel = ui.Panel({style: {width: '300px'}});
var slider = ui.Slider({min: 0, max: 1, value: 0.3, step: 0.1});
var button = ui.Button({label: 'Analizar', onClick: runAnalysis});

panel.add(ui.Label('Mi App de Análisis'));
panel.add(slider);
panel.add(button);
ui.root.add(panel);
```
- Publicar vía Code Editor: Assets → Scripts → Publish
- Se despliega en: `{username}.users.earthengine.app/view/{appname}`

### Desplegar en App Engine:
- Usar Service Account para autenticación server-side
- Usuarios NO necesitan ser usuarios registrados de Earth Engine
- Ejemplo: Flask/Django backend + Earth Engine + Maps frontend

---

## 10. KML/KMZ

### Estructura KML básica:
```xml
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<kml xmlns="http://www.opengis.net/kml/2.2">
  <Document>
    <name>Mi Mapa</name>
    <Placemark>
      <name>Santiago</name>
      <description>Capital de Chile</description>
      <Point>
        <coordinates>-70.6506,-33.4489,0</coordinates>
      </Point>
    </Placemark>
    <Placemark>
      <name>Área de estudio</name>
      <Polygon>
        <outerBoundaryIs>
          <LinearRing>
            <coordinates>
              -70.68,-33.47,0
              -70.63,-33.47,0
              -70.63,-33.42,0
              -70.68,-33.42,0
              -70.68,-33.47,0
            </coordinates>
          </LinearRing>
        </outerBoundaryIs>
      </Polygon>
    </Placemark>
  </Document>
</kml>
```

### Uso en Google Maps JavaScript API:
```javascript
var kmlLayer = new google.maps.KmlLayer({
  url: 'https://mi-servidor.com/datos.kml',
  map: map
});
```

### Límites KML en Google Maps:
- Archivo: 3MB comprimido, 10MB descomprimido
- Imágenes: 500KB por KMZ
- Features: 1,000 por documento
- Network links: máximo 10

---

## 11. Photorealistic 3D Tiles

### Acceso:
```
Root tileset URL:
https://tile.googleapis.com/v1/3dtiles/root.json?key={API_KEY}
```

### Integración con CesiumJS:
```javascript
const viewer = new Cesium.Viewer('cesiumContainer');
const tileset = viewer.scene.primitives.add(
  new Cesium.Cesium3DTileset({
    url: `https://tile.googleapis.com/v1/3dtiles/root.json?key=${API_KEY}`
  })
);
```

### Integración con deck.gl:
```javascript
import {Tile3DLayer} from '@deck.gl/geo-layers';

const layer = new Tile3DLayer({
  id: 'google-3d-tiles',
  data: `https://tile.googleapis.com/v1/3dtiles/root.json?key=${API_KEY}`,
  loadOptions: {
    fetch: {headers: {'X-GOOG-API-KEY': API_KEY}}
  }
});
```

### Renderers soportados:
- CesiumJS (v1.91+)
- Cesium for Unreal (v1.12+)
- Cesium for Unity
- deck.gl (v8.9.13+)
- Formato: OGC 3D Tiles standard (glTF)

---

## 12. Conexión Earth Engine ↔ ArcGIS

### Exportar de GEE a ArcGIS:
```python
import ee
from arcgis.gis import GIS
from arcgis.features import FeatureLayer

# 1. Exportar de Earth Engine a GeoJSON/GeoTIFF
ee.Initialize(project='mi-proyecto')
collection = ee.FeatureCollection('...')
task = ee.batch.Export.table.toDrive(
    collection=collection,
    description='export',
    fileFormat='GeoJSON'
)
task.start()

# 2. Subir a ArcGIS Online
gis = GIS("https://www.arcgis.com", "user", "pass")
item = gis.content.add({"title": "Datos GEE"}, data="export.geojson")
published = item.publish()
```

### Usar servicios ArcGIS en Earth Engine:
```python
# Cargar FeatureCollection desde URL (GeoJSON endpoint)
# Earth Engine puede consumir datos vectoriales vía ee.FeatureCollection
fc = ee.FeatureCollection('projects/mi-proyecto/assets/datos_arcgis')
```

